Original message: Wow, thanks for that @IGassmann, until there is a working version, I think we may switch to that instead of patching Next.js internals! 🙌

Short version derived from the link above for those who don't want to click:

```ts
function invalidate(cache: any) {
  Object.keys(cache).forEach(key => delete cache[key]);
}

/**
 * Next currently prefetches the page of every visible Link on the page
 * For every prefetch request, the middleware runs and the response is cached in window.next.router.sdc or window.next.router.sdc
 *
 * Imagine a scenario with a /protected page requiring the user to be signed in using middleware.
 * If we don't invalidate the cache, we end up in the following redirect flow:
 * home -> /protected -> middleware redirects to /sign-in -> perform sign-in
 *            -> try to navigate to /protected but the cached 307 response is used
 *                   -> redirect to /sign-in instead -> withRedirectToHome -> home
 * When the auth state changes and the middleware runs again, the client-side router does not automatically invalidate the cache so the browser follows the cached response
 *
 * This helper invalidates both known caches help prevent the scenario described above.
 */
export function invalidateNextRouterCache() {
  if (typeof window === 'undefined') return;

  try {
    // delete the keys without nuking the cache by reassigning the variable to an empty object, in case next holds a reference to it
    invalidate((window as any).next.router.sdc);
    invalidate((window as any).next.router.sbc);
  } catch (e) { /* Swallow error */ }
};
```

