@zuinqstudio You can call `router.refresh()` in the on click event handler. this is a more actualised workaround : 

```tsx
'use client';

import { useRouter } from 'next/navigation';
import { forwardRef, startTransition } from 'react';

const DynamicLink = forwardRef<
  HTMLAnchorElement,
  Omit<React.HTMLProps<HTMLAnchorElement>, 'ref'>
>(({ href, children, ...props }, ref) => {
  const router = useRouter();

  return (
    <a
      {...props}
      ref={ref}
      href={href}
      onClick={(e) => {
        e.preventDefault();
        startTransition(() => {
          router.push(href); 
          router.refresh();
       });
      }}
    >
      {children}
    </a>
  );
});

export default DynamicLink;
```
 
- `router.refresh()` wipes the client-side cache, so it would need to refetch the page when navigating, only downside is that all of your pages (even static ones) will need to call the server before navigating, for these it will be fast since next will just return the built page from the cache, but you still have a roundtrip there 
- I added `startTransition` to tell react to not block the rendering while navigating, so if your page takes a little while to load, you could still interact with the rest of the app.

